elements.name: Preferred IDE
elements.documentation:
The IMCE (SSCAE) Yoxos Level 4 profile is the standard Eclipse setup to use if you'll need to work with MagicDraw classpaths or anything QVT related. It is also a bit bloated and slow. An alternate "lite" profile has been created that uses the JEE distro as a base and adds in all the QVT and IMCE support needed that you can try instead. (link TBD)

If you don't need anything MagicDraw or QVT related, (like only working on view editor or web apps), then choose any Eclipse setup you like. Recommended is the JEE distro with Pydev, Subclipse and EGit plugins.

elements.name: MDK (DocGen 3)
elements.documentation: Checkout DocGen code at https://sscae-cm.jpl.nasa.gov/svn/mbee/trunk/MD17.0.2SP3/MDK/. There should already be a DocGen launch config to run or debug. You will need to fill in the md.install.dir variable in order for the launcher to work.

elements.name: gov.nasa.jpl.mbee.lib
elements.documentation: Contains utility classes and methods for filtering, collecting, converting model elements and running scripts. Anything that can be reused. Available to userscripts.

elements.name: gov.nasa.jpl.mgss.mbee.docgen
elements.documentation: Contains classes for configuring and initializing the plugin, profile stereotype strings, and DocGen specific utilities.

elements.name: gov.nasa.jpl.mgss.mbee.docgen.actions
elements.documentation: Contains classes that represent actions that can be triggered from the Magicdraw GUI (mostly right click menu items). The appearance of these menu actions depends on what the user has right clicked on.

elements.name: gov.nasa.jpl.mgss.mbee.docgen.dgvalidation
elements.documentation: This contains similar classes and code to the dgview package, is auto generated from the dgvalidation ecore model to support qvt scripts as validation scripts.

elements.name: gov.nasa.jpl.mgss.mbee.docgen.dgview
elements.documentation: This package and subpackages contain auto generated emf classes and code from the dgview ecore metamodel. This is to support qvt scripts so they can return the view element equivalent objects.

elements.name: gov.nasa.jpl.mgss.mbee.docgen.docbook
elements.documentation: Contains classes that represent a stripped down version of the basic elements in a document - paragraph, image, table, list, section and visitors that operate on them.

elements.name: gov.nasa.jpl.mgss.mbee.docgen.generator
elements.documentation: Contains the core classes for parsing the document model and generating and validating it.

elements.name: gov.nasa.jpl.mgss.mbee.docgen.model
elements.documentation: Contains classes that represent the elements in the document profile - built in queries and the view hierarchy.

elements.name: gov.nasa.jpl.mgss.mbee.docgen.table
elements.documentation: Contains classes that deals with tables - for examples, non trivial queries that produce tables and/or editable tables.

elements.name: gov.nasa.jpl.mgss.mbee.docgen.validation
elements.documentation: Contains classes that represent validation suites and rules that are used by built in or user validation queries.

elements.name: gov.nasa.jpl.mgss.mbee.docgen.viewedit
elements.documentation: Contains classes that produce or ingest information to/from the view editor.

elements.name: Very Important Classes
elements.documentation: This shows the classes that are responsible for validating and generating a document and adding menu items that trigger those actions.

elements.name: Model Visitors
elements.documentation: This shows the classes that represent the structure and queries of views and the visitors that analyze or transform them.

elements.name: Docbook Visitors
elements.documentation: This shows the core classes that represent basic elements in a document or view - paragraphs, tables, images, lists, and the visitors that analyze or serialize them for output.

elements.name: Main Flows
elements.documentation: These are the most common threads that show how the core DocGen classes are called and used - Generate Document, Export View, Export View Comments, and how stuff in the right click menu are populated. Gnarly details are omitted.

elements.name: Docbook XML Report Generation Flow
elements.documentation: This shows the thread of calls for generating a Docbook XML report through the GUI.

elements.name: Export to View Editor Flow
elements.documentation: This shows the thread of export a document or view to the view editor.

elements.name: Export View Editor Comments Flow
elements.documentation: This shows the thread of exporting view comments to the view editor.

elements.name: Populate Right Click Menu
elements.documentation: This shows how the right menu items gets populated when a user right clicks on a view in Magicdraw.

elements.name: DocWeb
elements.documentation:
DocWeb is a Django app. The current codebase is in git - https://mbse.jpl.nasa.gov/stash/projects/MBEE/repos/docweb/browse and includes a copy of fop and the xsl stylesheets from Oxygen 13.2 with customizations. The deployed DocWeb is not yet pointing to this repository though, that'll be done sometime. So any immediate fixes will need to be propagated to the server by hand.

On the docgen server, docweb is at /data/www/docweb/production.

The apache httpd server is at /data/www/httpd-2.2.23, conf files are in conf subdirectory.

To restart the server, login to docgen and restart the httpd process.

  

sudo /etc/init.d/httpd restart

elements.name: Admin
elements.documentation:
To handle new document requests or whatever, go to the django admin at https://docweb.jpl.nasa.gov/app/admin/.

To add a new document:

  1. Add the Tw_project (the actual teamwork project name) if it doesn't already exist and associate it with the right server
  2. Add the Project (the tab on docweb) if it doesn't already exist, associate with the ldap group(s). Ldap groups would already exist if someone in that group has logged in to docweb before. If not, just create it and tell whoever's in that group to log out and log back in.
  3. Add the category if it doesn't already exist, associate with the Project
  4. Add the Document. The name should be the name of the DocumentView element of the document. Associate with the right category and Tw_project.

Clicking on the Jobs would result in server error. This is due to a schema that's a bit backwards and resulted in some failed requests having null pointers or something. We never bothered to fix it since it doesn't affect the site that much. Do not keep clicking on Jobs just to see the bunnies.

elements.name: MD Servers
elements.documentation:
Do all of the following as the www user!

DocWeb currently supports teamwork servers 17021, 17022, 17023, 17024. There's a separate Magicdraw installation for each on docgen server, in /data/www/magicdraw.

 MD Version  Directory  Teamwork  Service Port
 17.0.2 SP3 build 1039  MagicDrawUML1702-1  17023  8002
 17.0.2 SP3 build 1039  MagicDrawUML1702-2  17022  8004
 17.0.2 SP3 build 1039  MagicDrawUML1702-3  17024  8005
 17.0.2 SP3 build 1039  MagicDrawUML1702-4  17021  8006

There is a checkout of MDK and MSMDK profiles trunk and branch in /data/www/magicdraw. All installations are symlinked to these directories - all to trunk except for 17022 for opsrev development. DocGenUserScripts trunk and branch are also symlinked. DocGenUserScripts checkout are from MSMDK and subdirectories inside are checked out from MDK. To do updates, do svn update inside DocGenUserScripts subdirectories.

For DocGen plugin jar updates or profile updates, there's no need to reinstall the whole thing. Just update the relevant jar and profile for each installation. Then go to 

/data/www/docgen-service/bin
and do 
./restart.sh

as the www user to restart all servers.

To restart individual servers, search for the specific md process 

ps -eaf | grep 1702-1
and 
kill processid
In 
/data/www/docgen-service/bin
there are mdserver0xx.sh and config0xx.properties files that correspond to each installation. To start a particular one, do 
./mdserver023.sh config023.properties > LOG023 &
The LOG023 indicates when the server is ready and outputs memory usage every hour. The actual md log is in its usual place inside each installation directory.

The headless server code is at https://mbse.jpl.nasa.gov/stash/projects/MBEE/repos/mdserver/browse.

elements.name: Troubleshooting
elements.documentation:
If something goes wrong:

  1. Trouble generating or transforming documents
    • If there's a log on docweb for the generation
      • If there's some exception about index out of bounds right after trying to load project, chances are project wasn't loaded. Causes can be missing profiles/modules, permission problems, etc.
      • Out of memory after trying to load project - restart server, maybe
      • Out of memory after generating and uploading to docweb (usually within fop output) - fop ran out of memory, only seen this with super big documents like Marc's. Can try upping the Xmx in the bottom of fop script at /data/www/docweb/production/fop-1.0/fop
      • Try to divine other information from the log, good luck!
    • If there isn't a log (this is cumbersome, should add more features to help in this)
      • Use a mysql database client and connect to the database docweb_production on docgen server (use ssh tunnel). Look at the recent entries in table ondemand_request, ticket column. Figure out which ticket belongs to the failed request.
      • Documents are generated first into /data/www/docgen-service/tmp under a directory with ticket name. check to see if it's there and if anything actually got generated.
      • If it was generated, in rare cases, if the zipped up version is too big, it can fail to be uploaded to docweb from MDServer (even though right now they're both on the same machine MDServer uploads the output to docweb through http because we thought they could be on different machines in the future)
      • Also check /data/www/docgen-service/web, but DO NOT DO LS IN HERE unless you want to wait a looong time. This is where all the generated documents are kept under their tickets. The directory structure needs a revamp to prevent thousands of directories here.
      • Detective time! Good Luck!
    • If all else fails
      • Check the magicdraw log file inside the corresponding installation dir and see if it's illuminating. if not,
      • log in to docgen with -XY flag, do 
        chmod +r .Xauthority
        then switch to www user and 
        cp /home/you/.Xauthority ./
        this allows www to bring up the actual magicdraw gui on docgen. Shutdown that server first. Maybe there's some dialog box preventing it to properly open projects. Go into the bin directory of whichever magicdraw install was used for the problem document and try to open it on the server by 
        ./mduml
  2. If something's wrong with docweb app
    • If users are not seeing project tabs and they're in the right groups, tell them to log out and log back in
    • if sleeping bunnies:
      • There's a bug in docweb where if people tagged or favorited a document generation and it was later deleted, the association remained and now points to null and results in exceptions. This needs to be fixed, in the meantime...edit the database and delete those associations, you may need some detective work to figure which rows are problematic. See the tag_tag_instance or favorite_favorite table.
    • if not responding:
      • check the httpd logs in /data/www/httpd-2.2.23/logs
      • we've experienced dos-like probes by jpl's security or web crawler, check the log files aren't huge
      • out of disk space from huge logs - rare
      • restart httpd
    • if all else fails: panic

elements.name: View Editor
elements.documentation:
Do everything below as the www user!

View editor is currently hosted on the mbee server. The apache installation is at /data/www/apache-tomcat-7.0.30. The startup.sh file in bin has a line added at the top to export env var for the sesame data location.

Code is here: https://mbse.jpl.nasa.gov/stash/projects/MBEE/repos/editor/browse. Best eclipse to use is the Eclipse JEE distribution. You'll also need Tomcat 7 (and Tomcat 6 for setting up the sesame repo, but details elsewhere).If someone accidentally pushed some project tab and want it deleted, there's no easy way to do it right now, view editor should add in an interface sometime. To delete it:

  1. shut down the view editor tomcat 7 (shutdown.sh in /data/www/apache-tomcat-7.0.30/bin)
  2. start the sesame web interface - this is in tomcat 6 (startup.sh in /data/www/apache-tomcat-6.0.35/bin, this also has an edit on top for the sesame env var)
  3. make edits by going to http://mbee:8080/openrdf-workbench/repositories/editor/summary
    1. find out which resource is the project element
    2. go to Remove, and remove all triple for that subject
  4. shutdown tomcat 6
  5. startup tomcat 7

elements.name: Test Procedures
elements.documentation:
Before release, do the following run through of MDK's view editor interface on the staging instance, currently hosted on http://docgen.jpl.nasa.gov:8080/staging. A test model is available on the 17023 teamwork server called ViewEditorTest.

  • Export View (Overwrites View Editor)
  • Import View
  • Validate Sync
  • Synchronize View
  • Export View Comments
  • Import View Comments
  • Export View Hierarchy
  • Organize Project
  • Delete Project or Document

elements.name: Development and Release Process
elements.documentation: MDK, DocWeb, and View Editor development and release workflows would initially be based on what is described here: http://nvie.com/posts/a-successful-git-branching-model/. Deviations may be added as we try it out. Special cases, such as supporting parallel releases for SSCAE and flight projects, and profile development will need further consideration. Stash also has documentation on this workflow: http://www.atlassian.com/git/workflows#!workflow-gitflow

elements.name: Collaboration with IMCE/SSCAE/COP
elements.documentation:
Products produced by the MBEE team are intended to be general purpose and used by the greater MBSE community at JPL. Extension and adaptation points are provided for projects who need special analysis or project specific queries. The goal is to leverage and support IMCE products and patterns as part of the platform, but allow projects to adapt and specialize if needed. The MBEE products will be built on IMCE and delivered to SSCAE as part of their release process.

Contributions by the community of practice can also be considered for inclusion into the SSCAE packaged releases. Criteria and process TBD.

elements.name: Communicating Changes
elements.documentation: This is to make sure changes in API or profiles on either side are communicated if it can affect the other.

elements.name: Git Process
elements.documentation: The following sections describe the commands and workflow for working with the git repository.

elements.name: Master and Develop Branches
elements.documentation:
The master branch should always contain the latest production code. This branch should be what the CI server pulls from for release builds.

Develop branch should contain the latest integrated development code. This should be what the CI server pulls from for developer builds.

elements.name: New Features, Major Bug Fixes, Experiments
elements.documentation: This describes the process for working on new features and bug fixes and integrating them into develop branch when done. This process applies to CODE ONLY and NOT any MagicDraw produced artifacts like profiles/modules/diagram descriptors/etc.

elements.name: Release
elements.documentation: This is the process for preparing and releasing a new release.

elements.name: Critical Bug Fixes
elements.documentation: This is the process for making critical bug fixes on a released version.

elements.name: Profile Changes
elements.documentation:
Special consideration for making profile changes. Because MagicDraw profiles should not be "merged" casually, changes should ideally always be done on a single branch and pushed to all other branches. If 2 in work features need a profile change, the changes CANNOT be done in each branch and merged later. (this MAY work depending on what the change is or how git merges the mdxml, but it's asking for disaster and heartbreak)

Profile change proposals should be communicated to everyone who's working in the repository. ONE person makes the necessary changes in the 'develop' branch and every new feature should branch after that. (Profile change would ideally be done before any feature branch that needs it) Otherwise, feature branches should get a copy of the updated profile or do a merge from develop.

elements.name: MDK Parallel and/or Future Releases
elements.documentation:
There is a possibility of MDK having to support Europa on a more frequent release schedule than SSCAE. Initially we can have the same releases for EHM and SSCAE, changes to workflow and branching strategy may need to be adjusted as needed. Preliminary plan is to have a separate sscae-master branch and follow the same release process using the same develop branch.

If it gets to the point where SSCAE needs diverging changes or fixes from what's released for Europa, a separate sscae-develop branch can be created from develop. Non-conflicting features can follow the same process but merge into both develop and sscae-develop. Hopfully we won't have to do that - can revisit if and when needed.

For the next major version of MDK (DocGen 4), major profile and code changes are anticipated and a possible fork to a new repository is planned instead of having a branch that will never get merged in.
